The first gondola at Les Gets was installed in 1973 on the Chavannes side (a detachable 6-seater cabin).


The current gondola cabin is a compact, enclosed pod offering panoramic, secure alpine views. Technically, while cabins are carried continuously by the cable, they detach via a detachable grip system on arrival at the station. This allows the cabin to slow down for safe boarding and unloading, while the cable itself keeps its constant speed.

vehicles.name: IDF télécabine (RHT)
vehicles.description: Le 1er téléphérique d’Île-de-France viendra compléter l’offre de transport du réseau francilien à l’horizon 2025. À sa mise en service, le Câble C1 reliera directement les villes de Villeneuve-Saint-Georges, Limeil-Brévannes et Valenton au Métro 8 Créteil – Pointe du Lac. Ce mode de transport attractif et innovant apportera une réponse concrète aux difficultés quotidiennes de déplacement des habitants de ces villes du Val-de-Marne.

vehicles.name: TGV Postal Cab (F) (P5)
vehicles.description:
Power car facing forwards, with the pantograph up to 5 blocks height.

The TGV Postal was introduced in 1984 and is instantly recognizable by its bright yellow La Poste livery. Based on modified TGV Sud-Est (PSE) units, the postal variants had their passenger compartments replaced with spacious cargo areas capable of holding up to 100 tons of mail and parcels. Operating primarily on overnight routes between Paris and Lyon , they could reach speeds of 270 km/h, dramatically cutting delivery times. For three decades, these specialized trains silently whisked letters and packages across France until changing postal needs led to their retirement in 2015.

vehicles.name: TGV VEGV Mélusine (Gray livery)
vehicles.description:
Should be inserted between the power car and end passenger car of a TGV.

Once the guardian angel of France's high-speed lines, this specialized vehicle meticulously monitored track conditions, overhead wires, and signaling systems while traveling at full operational speeds. Though left to weather in a maintenance yard after newer technology replaced it, Mélusine still houses some of the most precise rail diagnostics ever developed. 

Please, won't you commission it for a run from time to time?
